# SkillShare Quickstart for Team Members

This guide sets up your machine to receive the Packaged Agile team's shared AI skills. You only do this **once**. After that, getting updates is two commands.

> Not comfortable in PowerShell? Open **Claude Code**, **OpenAI Codex**, or **OpenCode** and paste the prompt at the end of this guide. Your AI assistant will run the commands for you.

## Before you start

- Ask **Dave** to invite your GitHub account to the `packaged-agile` organization, then **accept the invite** (check the email tied to your GitHub account).
- You need a Windows PC with **PowerShell**. (Mac and Linux work too; the commands are the same except where noted.)

## Step 0 - Install the GitHub CLI and sign in (one time)

Our skill library is **private**, so your machine needs permission to reach it.

```powershell
# Install the GitHub CLI (skip if you already have it)
winget install --id GitHub.cli

# Sign in with your browser
gh auth login
```

When prompted, choose: **GitHub.com -> HTTPS -> Login with a web browser.** Then let git reuse that sign-in so you are not asked to log in twice:

```powershell
gh auth setup-git
```

✓ Logged in to github.com as <username> (oauth token saved to keyring).

## Step 1 - Install SkillShare

```powershell
irm https://raw.githubusercontent.com/runkids/skillshare/main/install.ps1 | iex
```

**Important:** SkillShare will not be recognized in this window yet. **Close and reopen PowerShell**, then confirm:

```powershell
skillshare --version
```

(If it still is not found, try `ss --version`. `ss` is the shorthand.)

✓ skillshare v0.20.21

## Step 2 - Point SkillShare at your AI tool (one time)

Tell SkillShare which AI tool to deliver skills to. Replace `opencode` below with the tool you use:

| Your AI tool | Use this target name |
|--------------|---------------------|
| OpenCode | `opencode` |
| Claude Code | `claude` |
| OpenAI Codex | `codex` |

```powershell
skillshare init --targets opencode --no-copy --no-git --no-skill
```

Use more than one? Comma-separate them: `--targets opencode,claude`.

> **Claude Desktop or Claude Cowork?** These chat apps have no skills folder, so SkillShare cannot auto-deliver. Skip this step and open a skill's `SKILL.md`, pasting the guidance into your chat when you need it. (Or use OpenCode / Claude Code for automatic delivery.)

✓ Initialized with targets: opencode

## Step 3 - Connect to the shared skill library

```powershell
skillshare install github.com/packaged-agile/skillshare-skills --track
```

The `--track` flag remembers this library so updates are easy. You will see a short security scan run. That is normal.

> **Note:** you cannot add `--all` or `--yes` to a `--track` install (SkillShare blocks that combination). Just run the command as shown; it finishes on its own.

Want only some skills? List them:

```powershell
skillshare install github.com/packaged-agile/skillshare-skills --track -s humanizer,retrospective
```

✓ Installed 5 skills from packaged-agile/skillshare-skills

## Step 4 - Send the skills to your AI tool

```powershell
skillshare sync
```

Done. Your AI assistant now knows the Packaged Agile skills.

✓ Synced 5 skills to opencode target

## Updating later (the everyday command)

When Dave adds or improves a skill:

```powershell
skillshare update --all
skillshare sync
```

## A note on `markdown-pdf-publisher`

This skill turns documents into branded PDFs. It needs **Node.js** on your machine and runs an npm package (Vivliostyle) to build the PDF. SkillShare's security scan flags it as **medium** for that reason. If you do not need PDF publishing, skip it:

```powershell
skillshare install github.com/packaged-agile/skillshare-skills --track --exclude markdown-pdf-publisher
```

## If something goes wrong

Full troubleshooting is in **[skillshare-operations-guide.md](skillshare-operations-guide.md)**. The most common fixes:

- **`skillshare` not recognized** -> close and reopen PowerShell.
- **A full-screen list of AI tools appeared** -> that is the target picker. Select yours with arrow keys + Space, then Enter. (Running Step 2 first avoids it entirely.)
- **`install` asks you to log in again** -> run `gh auth setup-git`, then retry.
- **`gh auth login` fails** -> check you have a GitHub account. Try `winget uninstall GitHub.cli` then reinstall.
- **`skillshare init` shows the TUI** -> press Ctrl+C, then run `skillshare init --targets opencode --no-copy --no-git --no-skill`.
- **`skillshare install` asks for login again** -> run `gh auth setup-git`, then retry.

## Not comfortable in PowerShell? Let your AI do it

Open **Claude Code**, **OpenAI Codex**, or **OpenCode** and paste this:

> Please install SkillShare and connect it to my team's shared skill library. Run these PowerShell commands one at a time and tell me the result of each before continuing:
>
> 1. `irm https://raw.githubusercontent.com/runkids/skillshare/main/install.ps1 | iex`
> 2. Close and reopen PowerShell, then run `skillshare --version`
> 3. `gh auth login` (choose GitHub.com, HTTPS, web browser), then `gh auth setup-git`
> 4. `skillshare init --targets opencode --no-copy --no-git --no-skill`
> 5. `skillshare install github.com/packaged-agile/skillshare-skills --track`
> 6. `skillshare sync`
>
> If any step fails, stop and tell me what went wrong before trying the next one.

